�ӼЪk  TRADEMARK  LAW
           �k�T�Ϣ�  ��  (�� �w ��)
Under the Trademark Law of the Republic of China, trademark are
granted on the basis of priority of registration rather than priority
of use.  An application for trademark registration has to specify
the design of the mark as well as the category of products the
mark will used.  Once the application is preliminarily approved,
the trademark is published in the official trademark gazette.
 If no oppositions are filed within three months subsequent to
the publication , the trademark is then registered.  The initial
registration lasts for ten years, within renewals allowed for
every ten years thereafter.

Trademark protection in general is available to all foreign entities.
 In particular, application from certain countries, through bilateral
treaties within Taiwan, do get the advantage of a priority registration
date if the applications were filed in their home jurisdiction
six months prior to the applications submitted in Taiwan.

An infringer infrigering valid trademark will be subject to a
criminal penalty up to three years imprisonment and severe civil
liabilities.

�M�Q�k  PATENT  LAW
           �k�T�Ϣ�  ��  (�� �w ��)
                     PATENT  LAW
Any invention or creation which maintains novelty ,utility and
non-obviously elements will be eligible to apply fjor patent registration.
 Protection under the Patent Law of the Republic of China is only
available to holders of patent registrations in Taiwan.  Patent
registration is granted on the priority of application basis.
 However, some benefits are offered upon foreign patent holders
under various bilatered agreements.  For instance, a foreign patent
application filing in Taiwan is entitled to claim a priority date
provided that the patent application is submitted within twelve
months after the patent filing for the same invention was made
in the foreign jurisdiction.

The examination process could take years to complete.  Once granted,
an invention patent is valid for twenty years from the date of
application and an annual administrative fee must be paid or the
patent may be canceled.  For utility patents the period of validity
is twelve years and for design patents is ten years.

The patent owner is able to claim a civil compensation from the
infringer of invention patent.  In case the infringer commit the
violation willfully, a penalty equal to three times of the damages
suffered by the patent holders may be imposed.  For infrigerment
of utility and design patent, a criminal liability up to two years
of imprisionment will be charged.

